// Paste these entries into ~/.config/zed/tasks.json (or
// %APPDATA%\Zed\tasks.json on Windows) for "AL: Download symbols" and
// "AL: Check symbols" in Zed's command palette under `task: spawn`.
//
// How it works:
//   1. You pick the task from the palette (Ctrl+Shift+P → task: spawn).
//   2. Zed runs the task's shell command in the project root.
//   3. The command writes one line into .alzed-trigger.txt.
//   4. The bridge (alzed-bridge.exe) is watching that file — it picks up
//      the command, fires the corresponding al/* request to the AL
//      Language Server, and deletes the trigger file.
//
// The bridge must be running for these to do anything, which it is
// whenever Zed has an AL workspace open.
//
// To sanity-check the bridge half *without* the task, open a terminal in
// your project root and run:
//
//     echo download-symbols > .alzed-trigger.txt
//
// You should see `trigger file detected` then `sending al/downloadSymbols`
// in the AL LSP log.
[
  {
    "label": "AL: Download symbols",
    "command": "echo download-symbols > .alzed-trigger.txt",
    "use_new_terminal": false,
    "allow_concurrent_runs": false,
    "reveal": "never",
    "tags": ["al"]
  },
  {
    "label": "AL: Check symbols",
    "command": "echo check-symbols > .alzed-trigger.txt",
    "use_new_terminal": false,
    "allow_concurrent_runs": false,
    "reveal": "never",
    "tags": ["al"]
  }
]
